For some reason, `repeat` argument is treated special.

```js
var yargs = require('yargs');
var assert = require('assert');

let args = yargs
    .parserConfiguration({
        'unknown-options-as-args': true
    })
    .option('known', { type: 'string' })
    .argv;

console.log('known:', args.known);
console.log('repeat:', args.repeat);
console.log('_:', args._);
    
assert.equal(args.known, 'x');
assert.equal(args.repeat, undefined);
assert.deepEqual(args._, [ '--repeat', '100', '--unknown', '200']);
```

Run as:

```
$ node index.js --known x --repeat 100 --unknown 200
```

The output is:

```
known: x
repeat: 100
_: [ '--unknown', '200' ]
```

I did not add any option named `repeat`, so I would expect this argument to end up in `_`.
However, it shows up as a named option, as if I had defined an option named `repeat`, or if I didn't use `unknown-options-as-args`.

Other unknown options are correctly put in `_`.
